<!-- Filling this template is mandatory -->

**Your checklist for this pull request**
- [x] I've read the [guidelines for contributing](https://github.com/rizinorg/rizin/blob/master/DEVELOPERS.md) to this repository
- [x] I made sure to follow the project's [coding style](https://github.com/rizinorg/rizin/blob/master/DEVELOPERS.md#code-style)
- [x] I've documented or updated the documentation of every function and struct this PR changes. If not so I've explained why.
- [x] I've added tests that prove my fix is effective or that my feature works (if possible)
- [ ] I've updated the [rizin book](https://github.com/rizinorg/book) with the relevant information (if needed)

**Detailed description**

<!-- Explain the **details** for making this change. Is a new feature implemented? What existing problem does the pull request solve? How does the pull request solve these issues? Please provide enough information so that others can review your pull request. -->

This PR intends to lift x86 ISA to RzIL. This is a GSoC 2022 project.
Relevant links:

 - [Rizin blogpost](https://rizin.re/gsoc/2022/#rzil-uplifting-migration-350-hour-project)
 - [My proposal](https://docs.google.com/document/d/17YUcgKswoamnGXMQ4TUefBMFRJl5mcWaE3HX-UvW_jk/edit?usp=sharing)

**Test plan**

<!-- What steps should the reviewer take to test your pull request? Demonstrate the code is solid. Example: The exact commands you ran and their output, screenshots/videos. This is your time to re-check that everything works and that you covered all the edge cases -->

Highlighted in the proposal document.

**Closing issues**

<!-- put "closes #XXXX" in your comment to auto-close the issue that your PR fixes (if any). -->

Tracker issue: #2080

**Notes**

This is only the first in series of a bunch of pull requests which plan on lifting x86. The IL implementation in the PR has not been semantically verified but the generated IL code has been type checked.

More info on the plan can be found here: https://dmaroo.github.io/gsocx86lifting

pr_body:
This PR adds tracing support for x86. This will be useful while testing rizinorg/rizin#2747 with `rz-tracetest`.

In it's current state, the generated trace can be successfully read by `libtrace`, and seems to be okay from manual inspection. ~~except it has wrong values for the `rawbytes` field. This results in invalid decompilation on Rizin's side, and therefore inability to use `rz-tracetest`. I believe the that the incorrect `rawbytes` value might be because of incorrect usage of `gen_trace_endframe`.~~

Unrelated changes:
 - This PR initializes an uninitialized variable `subqdict` to avoid compiler warnings
 - And changes the build file to use the correct paths for `bap-frames`
   - The compilation using the old build file failed with meson version `0.63.3`)
   - Although the current build file works, but I think there may be a neater way to do it than use directory traversal in the build file
